        "content": "{{short description|City in Zulia, Venezuela}}\n{{Infobox settlement |official_name = Ciudad Ojeda, Venezuela\n|nickname =  \"''La Ciudad Petrolera'' \", \"'Ojeda'\"\n|website=  [http://www.lagunillas-zulia.gob.ve/ Página web de la Alcaldía]\n|image_skyline=Ciudad Ojeda.jpg\n|image_caption=Panorama view of downtown San Matias area and Lake Maracaibo\n|image_flag=Bandera Lagunillas, Zulia.png\n|image_seal=Escudo de Lagunillas, Zulia.png\n|pushpin_map=Venezuela\n|subdivision_type  = Country\n|subdivision_type1 =  [[States of Venezuela|State]]\n|subdivision_type2 =  [[County|Counties]]\n|subdivision_type3 =  [[Demonym]]\n|subdivision_name  = [[Venezuela]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Zulia State|Zulia]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Lagunillas Municipality, Zulia|Lagunillas Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name3 = ''Citojense''\n|leader_title = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name = [[José Mosquera]] (2021–2025)\n|area_magnitude =\n|area_total_km2 = 975\n|postal_code_type = Postal code\n|postal_code = 4019\n|area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in Venezuela|Area code]]\n|area_code = 265\n|population_as_of = 2005\n|population_total = 128,941\n|population_density_km2 = 130\n|timezone = [[Venezuelan Standard Time Zone|VET]]\n|utc_offset =  &minus;4\n|elevation_m = 5\n|coordinates       = {{coord|10|12|0|N|71|18|0|W|region:VE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank1_name       = [[Köppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank1_info       = [[Tropical savanna climate|Aw]]\n|footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Ciudad Ojeda''' is a city located in the northeastern shore of [[Lake Maracaibo]] in [[Zulia State]] in northwestern [[Venezuela]]. Its population as of the 2005 census was listed as 128,941.{{Update inline|date=February 2023}}\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Ciudad Ojeda \"Plaza Alonso de Oejda\".jpg|250px|thumb|left|Alonso de Ojeda Square.]]\nCiudad Ojeda was founded on January 19, 1937, by President [[Eleazar López Contreras]] as a settlement for the inhabitants of Lagunillas de Aguas<ref>[http://www.efemeridesvenezolanas.com/html/ojeda.htm La Fundación de Ciudad Ojeda<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Today, it is a major center for the [[oil and gas industry]] in the [[Lake Maracaibo]] region.\n\nOn November 13, 1939, a terrible fire destroyed Lagunillas de Agua, causing over 200 fatalities. There are several hypotheses about the cause of the fire that prompted the final and decisive transfer of population to the mainland. The truth is that the oil industry was an oily layer on the lake, which had the potential to ignite the wooden houses built on stilts in the lake. One hypothesis is the accidental fall of a kerosene lamp to the lake from the Bar Caracas. Another is a fire caused by an oil company when he was going to beat his concession, that company helped reconstruction and retained the award after all, there is no evidence of this fact.<ref>[[:es:Lagunillas de Agua]]</ref>\n\n==Origin of the name==\nCiudad Ojeda was named in honor of [[Alonso de Ojeda]], the Spaniard who was the first European to discover Lake Maracaibo.\n\n==Population==\nCiudad Ojeda is medium-sized among Venezuelan cities, with a population of approximately 130,000 inhabitants. The majority of ''Citojenses'' are of [[Venezuelans|Venezuelan]] origin. It is also home to numerous foreign communities of [[Italian people|Italian]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]], [[Chinese people|Chinese]] and [[Arabs]] who have the biggest commercial businesses in the city.\n\n==Places of interest==\n*{{lang|es|Iglesia de Santa Lucia}} (Church of Santa Lucia) \n*{{lang|es|Casa de la Cultura}} (House of Culture)\n*{{lang|es|Muro de contencion del Lago de Maracaibo}} (Containment Wall of the ''Lago de Maracaibo'')\n*{{lang|es|Plaza Alonso de Ojeda}} (Alonso de Ojeda Square)\n*{{lang|es|Plaza Simón Bolívar}} (Simón Bolívar Square)\n*{{lang|es|El Mural Más Grande}} (The Biggest Mural)\n\n==Colleges and universities==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100105123959/http://www.uniojeda.edu.ve/ Universidad Alonso de Ojeda] - (''Uniojeda'')\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081103021608/http://www.unermb.edu.ve/ Universidad Nacional Experimental Rafael María Baralt] - (''UNERMB'')\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080429212245/http://www.iutpec.com/ Instituto Universitario Pedro Emilio Coll] - (IUTPEC)\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Denyse Floreano]] – [[Miss Venezuela 1994]]\n* [[Eddie Pérez (baseball)|Eddie Pérez]] – former Major League Baseball player and currently a catching coach for the [[Atlanta Braves]]\n* Mariángel Villasmil – [[Miss Venezuela 2020]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Zulia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1937]]\n\n{{Venezuela-geo-stub}}"
