        "title": "Houston Country Club",
        "content": "{{Short description|Country club in Houston, Texas}}\n{{Infobox golf facility\n|golf_facility_name = \n|image              = HoustonCC.logo.JPG\n|imagesize          = 260\n|caption            = \n|location           = [[Houston, Texas]]<br />[[United States]]\n|establishment      = 1908\n|type               = Private\n|owner              = <!-- name of organization/company -->\n|operator           = <!-- name of organization/company -->\n|holes              = 18\n|tournaments        = \n|website            = [http://www.houstoncc.com/ Houston Country Club]\n|course1            = <!-- individual course name, can leave blank if same as article title-->\n|designer1          = [[Tom McNamara (golfer)|Tom McNamara]] – 1908<br />[[Robert Trent Jones|Robert T. Jones]] – 1956<br />(re-design)\n|par1               = 72\n|length1            = {{convert|6,996|yd|abbr=on}}\nLongest hole is #12 - {{convert|597|yd|abbr=on}}\n|rating1            = 72.9\n|slope1             = 122\n|record1            = \n|image2             =\n|imagesize2         =\n|caption2           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Houston Country Club''' is a [[country club]] in the [[Tanglewood, Houston|Tanglewood]] area of [[Houston]], [[Texas]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Club house Houston Country Club Houston TX (1908-1924).jpg|thumb|left|150px|Clubhouse of the original Houston Country Club (1908-1924)]]\nFollowing the success of the first golf club organized in Houston (a nine-hole course built on 45 acres of land leased from [[Rice Institute|Rice University]] west of the city) the Houston Country Club was chartered in 1908. Under its first president William M. Rice Jr. it purchased and developed an 18-hole course southeast of [[downtown Houston]] on 152 acres.<ref>\"[https://ricehistorycorner.com/2020/12/04/a-few-timely-comments-from-mr-wm-m-rice-1938/ \"A few timely comments from Mr. Wm. M. Rice\", 1938]\" Rice History Blog. December 4, 2020.</ref> The country club moved to its current Tanglewood location in 1957. The former Houston Country Club was renamed the Houston Executive Club.\n\nThe City of Houston purchased the Houston Executive Club in 1972 and renamed it the Gus Wortham Golf Course.<ref>\"[http://www.houstontx.gov/municipalgolf/wortham/worthamrestoration.pdf Gus Wortham Golf Course Restoration Plan].\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20100528154510/http://www.houstontx.gov/municipalgolf/wortham/worthamrestoration.pdf Archive]) Houston Parks and Recreation Department. August 1, 2007. Retrieved on October 15, 2012.</ref> Claudia Feldman of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' said that in the 1960s Tanglewood residents mainly went to Houston Country Club exclusively, and that this was an example of the community's \"clubby atmosphere\".<ref name=Feldman>Feldman, Claudia. \"[http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=1992_1099189 Moving back to the 'hood . . ./CITIZEN BUSH].\" ''Houston Chronicle''. Sunday December 13, 1992. Lifestyle p. 1. Retrieved on October 15, 2012.</ref>\n\n[[George H. W. Bush]], a Tanglewood resident, often played golf and tennis at the club.<ref name=Feldman/> In the early 1960s Bush first met [[James Baker|James A. Baker]] and [[Robert Mosbacher]] while playing tennis at the Houston Country Club.<ref>Draper, Robert. \"[http://www.texasmonthly.com/preview/1992-08-01/feature5 Elephant Walk Visit].\" ''[[Texas Monthly]]''. August 1992. Retrieved on October 15, 2012. \"On the tennis courts of the Houston Country Club, Bush, Baker, and Mosbacher met each other for the first time during the early sixties.\"</ref> In the 1970s Bush and Baker's friendship progressed as they played tennis doubles.<ref>Thomas, Evan. \"[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NWEC&p_theme=nwec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11563F3A65410878&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM The Rescue Squad].\" ''[[Newsweek]]''. November 20, 2006. Retrieved on October 15, 2012. \"The two men became friends while playing doubles at the Houston Country Club in the 1970s\"</ref> Bush and Baker were the winners of the club's tennis doubles championships.<ref>Zeitlin, Maurice. \"[https://archive.today/20130131203503/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/102520987.html?dids=102520987:102520987&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+10,+1991&author=Maurice+Zeitlin.+Maurice+Zeitlin+is+a+professor+of&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=The+Cabinet:+A+Club+of+the+Rich+and+Well-Born&pqatl=google The Cabinet: A Club of the Rich and Well-Born].\" ''[[Newsday]]''. February 10, 1991. Start page 40. Retrieved on October 15, 2012. \"Cut from the same class mold, Bush's personal ties to the Untouchables reflect the way the men of his class mingle: Bush and [James A. Baker] belonged to the Houston Country Club and won its tennis doubles championships\"</ref>\n\nAround 1993 the Houston Country Club and some other area country clubs began claiming a new [[tax break]].<ref>\"[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D36EED9824E9&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM Country clubs claim tax break Houston, area schools lose revenue, paper says].\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]''. March 1, 1993. Retrieved on October 5, 2012. \"The River Oaks Country Club, Lakeside Country Club, the Houston Country Club and the Champions Golf Club are among the private clubs claiming the special[...]\"</ref> As of 2018, the Houston Country Club has a waiting list of people who wish to enter the club.<ref>Hveem, Todd. \"[http://www.chron.com/sports/golf/article/Lakeside-Country-Club-renovation-draws-rave-1700445.php Lakeside Country Club renovation draws rave reviews].\" ''Houston Chronicle''. Wednesday December 15, 2010. Retrieved on October 15, 2012. \"Lakeside, like River Oaks and Houston Country Club, has a waiting list.\"</ref>\n\n==Scorecard==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:HoustonCC-scorecard.JPG|560px]] -->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Texas|Tennis}}\n* [[River Oaks Country Club]]\n* [[Royal Oaks Country Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.houstoncc.com/ Houston Country Club]\n* [http://www.houstonparksboard.org/projects/documents/GWCBrochure2color.pdf Gus Wortham Golf Course Brochure] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20130531000807/http://houstonparksboard.org/projects/documents/GWCBrochure2color.pdf Archive]). Houston Parks Board.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|29.763|-95.489|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues in Houston]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1908]]"
