        "title": "Hasan Hayri",
        "content": "{{short description|Turkish politician}}\n\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n'''Hasan Hayri''' or '''Hasan Hayri Kanko''' ({{langx|ku|Hesen Xeyrî Beg}}) (b. 1881 (1497), Akpınar, Hozat, [[Tunceli]] - 1925), was a Kurdish politician from Dersim.<ref>[http://www.mamekiye.de/08/1163034013/1165588157/index_html?dateiname=1188321096 Hasan Hayri Kanko.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305124633/http://mamekiye.de/08/1163034013/1165588157/index_html?dateiname=1188321096 |date=2016-03-05 }} ''mamekiye.''</ref><ref>[http://www.radikal.com.tr/yazarlar/ayse-hur/sene-1921-kocgiri-isyani-aliser-ve-zarife-1124483/ Year 1921: Koçgiri rebellion, Aliser and Zarife (Turkish).] ''Radikal, 10 March 2013.''</ref>\n[[File:Hasan_Hayri.jpg|thumb|Hasan Hayri]]\n\n==Early life==\nHasanli was the son of Beyzade Murtaza Agha. After completing primary and secondary education in Dersim, he was taken to the Tribal Class of the [[Ottoman Military Academy]] on 3 October 1896. He was appointed to the 4th Army Siverek Tribal Cavalry Regiment, graduating with the rank of Lieutenant Cavalry on 24 February 1898.\n\n== Career ==\nWhile he was in charge of the Van Military Service Branch, he became a deputy of Dersim at the election held for the last period of the [[Chamber of Deputies (Ottoman Empire)|Meclis-i Mebusan]]. In 1920, he served as a deputy of Dersim in the first period of the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly]]:\n\nHe worked in the Parliament on Health and Social Aid, Petition, Economics, and National Defense Commissions.\n\nIn the [[Sheikh Said rebellion|Sheikh Said Rebellion]], Hasan Hayri was arrested and sentenced to death at the Eastern Independence Court, arguing that he participated in actions to help the insurgents.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe was married and had four children. His family received the surname \"Kanko\" (some sources say Kano).<ref>[http://www.xakk.net/archives/2246 Who was Ker Hesen? (Persian).] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714022825/http://www.xakk.net/archives/2246 |date=2018-07-14 }} ''Xaki Kurdistan, 21 April 2018.''</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 1923, [[Şerif Pasha]] demanded independence for the [[Kurdish people]] at the Congress of the [[Treaty of Lausanne]], where [[Turkish nationalism|Turkish nationalists]] were engaged in negotiations. [[Mustafa Kemal Atatürk|Atatürk]] ordered Hasan Hayri to go to parliament in [[Kurdish clothing|Kurdish clothes]], which were forbidden in Turkey, and testify that the Kurdish people did not want independence and wished to remain under Turkish governmental authority. Following the Congress of Lausanne, Hasan Hayri was arrested for wearing Kurdish clothes and for conspiracy against national security and was sentenced to death. He was hanged by Turkish forces following the court decision. Before his death he was asked his last request and said: \"bury my body in the way of Kurdish people, till any Kurd passes from there spitting on my grave.\" He called himself \"Ker Hesen\" (meaning Hasan the donkey, or idiot Hasan) and at the moment of hanging, shouted, \"Uh [[Sheikh Said]], Ker Hesen has been also martyred in the way of Kurdistan!\" Hasan Hayri became a symbol of betrayal among the Kurds.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018|reason=This would look better with a source backing it up}} The Turkish government replaced his grave years after his execution.<ref>[http://www.xakk.net/archives/2246 Who was Ker Hesen? (Persian).] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714022825/http://www.xakk.net/archives/2246 |date=2018-07-14 }} ''Xaki Kurdistan, 21 April 2018.''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hayri, Hasan}}\n[[Category:Ottoman military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People executed by Turkey by hanging]]\n[[Category:Sheikh Said rebellion]]\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hozat]]\n[[Category:Last Ottoman Parliamentary Assembly (1920) Tunceli Members]]\n[[Category:1st period Tunceli MPs]]\n[[Category:20th-century people from the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Military Academy Tribal Class alumni]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Army officers]]"
