        "title": "Murunda dynasty",
        "content": "{{Short description|Indian Dynasty}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2021}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2021}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n| conventional_long_name = Murunda dynasty\n| common_name            = Murunda dynasty\n| era                    = [[Middle Kingdoms of India|Classical India]]\n| year_start             = {{circa|2nd century CE}}\n| year_end               = {{circa|3rd century CE}}\n| religion               = [[Jainism]] {{Cn|date=November 2024}}\n| government_type        = Monarchy\n| capital                = \n| common_languages       = \n| p1                     = Mahameghavahana dynasty\n| s1                     = Gupta Empire\n| image_map = \n<mapframe text=\"[[Find spot]]s and places of issue of the Murunda inscriptions\" width=\"250\" height=\"250\" zoom=\"4\" longitude=\"86.5\" latitude=\"21\">\n{\n\t\"type\": \"FeatureCollection\",\n\t\"features\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"Feature\",\n\t\t\t\"properties\": { \"marker-symbol\": \"monument\", \"title\": \"Bhadrak\" },\n\t\t\t\"geometry\": { \"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [86.5, 21.06] }\n\t\t}\n\t]\n}\n</mapframe>\n}}\n\nThe '''Murunda dynasty''' ruled in the [[Utkal]] region of modern [[Odisha]] in eastern India during 2nd and 3rd centuries CE. Their territory included parts of the area around the northern districts of coastal [[Odisha]]. They appear to have succeeded the [[Mahameghavahana dynasty]] and then replaced by [[Nagas of Vindhyatabi]] and the [[Gupta Empire]].\n\n==Rulers==\n\nThe following members of the Murunda family are known:\n*Gana (2nd cen CE)\n*Dhamadamadhara (Dharmatamadharasya) (3rd cen CE) {{Cn|date=November 2024}}\n\n==History==\nThe Murunda dynasty likely ruled Utkala around the 2nd century and 3rd century CE.\n\n===Gana===\nMuch of the information about King Gana is known from the Bhadrak inscription<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/44156572 |publisher=Indian History Congress |last=Mohanty |first=Prafulla Kumar |title=Growth of Urban Society in Early Odisha |journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress |date=2015 |volume=76 |page=114 |jstor= 44156572 }}</ref><ref name=\"epigraphica\" >{{citation |url=https://archive.org/details/epigraphia-indica/epigraphia-indica-vol-29/|section=No. 23 — BHADRAK INSCRIPTION OF GANA ; REGNAL YEAR 8|section-url=https://archive.org/details/epigraphia-indica/epigraphia-indica-vol-29/page/n323/mode/2up?view=theater |title=Epigraphia Indica Volume 29 |pages=169–174 |last=Sircar|first=Dineshchandra|editor-last=Chhabra|editor-first=Bahadur Chand|date=January 1951 |publisher=[[Epigraphia Indica|Archaeological Survey of India]]|access-date=14 April 2021|id=EAN·UCC-13 5010010006895}}</ref> which was issued in the 8th regnal year during his reign. The inscription was found near Bhadrakali Temple which brought there from the neighbouring village.{{sfn|Sircar|1951|p=170}} The language of the inscription is in Prakrit written in Middle or Kushana [[Brahmi script]]. The inscription refers to the land grant given by Maharaja Gana to the residents of Panida.{{sfn|Sircar|1951|p=174}}\n\n===Dhamadamadhara===\nDhamadamadhara ruled over the region in around 3rd century CE. Under his reign, it has been noted that there were important diplomatic relations between [[Kalinga (historical region)|Kalinga]] and [[Funan]]. The Funan kingdom was co-founded by the merchant [[Kaundinya I]] from Kalinga when he married the Funanese princess [[Queen Soma|Soma]].<ref name=\"review\" >{{citation |url=http://magazines.odisha.gov.in/Orissareview/2011/Nov/engpdf/32-38.pdf |title=Kalinga and Funan : A Study in Ancient Relations |author=Benudhar Patra |date=November 2011 |publisher=Orissa Review |access-date=4 April 2021}}</ref> During 3rd cen CE, King Dhamadamadhara (Dharmatamadharasya) received the envoy Su-Wu representing King Fan Chan of Funan (225-250 CE) at the port of [[Tamralipti]].<ref name=\"Pelliot\" >{{cite journal |last=Pelliot |first=Paul |author-link1= Paul Pelliot |date=1903 |title=Le Fou-nan |url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/befeo_0336-1519_1903_num_3_1_1216 |access-date=12 April 2021 |language=fr |journal=Bulletin de l'École française d'Extrême-Orient |volume=3 |page=292 |doi=10.3406/befeo.1903.1216 }}</ref><ref name=\"GCoedes\" >{{cite book |last= Coedès |first= George |editor=Walter F. Vella |others=trans.Susan Brown Cowing |title=The Indianized States of Southeast Asia|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/115019/2/b11055005.pdf |year=1968 |pages=46–47 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-0368-1 }}</ref> Dhamadamadhara's rule over Kalinga is also attested from the discovery of a gold coin from [[Sisupalgarh]], on whose obverse his name has been inscribed. The king presented the envoy Su-Wu with four horses and it quite likely there were strong trade and cultural interactions between the two kingdoms.<ref name=\"review\" />\n\n==Inscriptions==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Find spot !! Issued by !! Regnal year !! Purpose\n|-\n| Bhadrak || Gana || 8 || Grant\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Odisha}}\n\n[[Category:Dynasties of India]]\n[[Category:History of Odisha]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of Odisha]]"
