        "content": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2023}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| year = 1934\n| team = Kentucky State Thorobreds\n| sport = football\n| image =\n| image_size = \n| conference = [[Midwest Athletic Association]]\n| short_conf = MAA\n| record = 8–0\n| conf_record = \n| head_coach= [[Henry Kean]]\n| hc_year = 4th\n| captain = \n| stadium = \n| champion = [[Black college football national championship|Black college national champion]]<br>MAA champion \n}}\nThe '''1934 Kentucky State Thorobreds football team''' was an [[American football]] team that represented Kentucky State Industrial College (now known as [[Kentucky State University]]) as a member of the [[Midwest Athletic Association]] (MAA) during the [[1934 college football season]]. In their fourth season under head coach [[Henry Kean]], the team compiled an 8–0 record, won the MAA championship, shut out seven of eight opponents, and outscored all opponents by a total of 193 to 2. The team was recognized as the [[black college football national championship|black college national champion]]. The team played its home games at Alumni Field in [[Frankfort, Kentucky]]. Notable players included [[Joe Kendall (American football)|Joe \"Tarzan\" Kendall]], an inductee of the [[College Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/the-pittsburgh-courier-the-all-american/130342120/ |title=The All-American Eleven! |first=Chester L. |last=Washington |authorlink=Chester L. Washington |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Courier]] |pages=2–5 |date=December 29, 1934 |accessdate=August 20, 2023 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| attend = y\n| source = y\n\n|October 6|at|{{cfb link|year=1934|team=West Virginia State Yellow Jackets|title=West Virginia State}}||[[Institute, WV]]|W 14-0||\n\n|October 13||{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Wilberforce Green Wave|title=Wilberforce}}||[[Frankfort, KY]]|W 15-0||<ref>{{cite news|title=Wilberforce Goes Down To Defeat|newspaper=The Sunday Times-Signal|date=October 14, 1934|page=11|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39628624/wilberforce_goes_down_to_defeat/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|October 27|vs|{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Tuskegee Golden Tigers|title=Tuskegee}}|[[Crosley Field]]|[[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, OH]]|W 6-2||<ref>{{cite news|title=Kentucky Team Beats Tuskegee|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|date=October 28, 1934|page=27|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39628287/kentucky_team_beats_tuskegee/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|November 3||{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Morris Brown Wolverines|title=Morris Brown}}|Alumni Field|Frankfort, KY|W 21-0||<ref>{{cite news|title=Kentucky State Thorobreds Beat Morris Brown, 20 To 0 In Thriller|newspaper=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=November 10, 1934|page=14|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39629053/kentucky_state_thorobreds_beat_morris/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|November 10||{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Fisk Bulldogs|title=Fisk}}||Frankfort, KY|W 44-0||<ref>{{cite news|title=K.S.I.C. Swamps Fisk University By 41 To 0|newspaper=The Courier-Journal|date=November 11, 1934|page=IV-11|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39628031/ksic_swamps_fisk/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|November 17|at|{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Lincoln Blue Tigers|title=Lincoln (MO)}}||[[Jefferson City, MO]]|W 33-0||<ref>{{cite news|title=Lincoln U. Is Beaten 33-0|newspaper=The Sunday News and Tribune|date=November 18, 1934|page=15A|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39629258/lincoln_u_is_beaten_330/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|November 24||{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Louisville Municipal Bantams|title=Louisville Municipal}}|Alumni Field|Frankfort, KY|W 27-0||<ref>{{cite news|title=K.S.I.C. Beats Municipal 27-0|newspaper=The Courier-Journal|date=November 25, 1934|page=V-3|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39627857/ksic_beats_municipal_270/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n|December 8|at|{{cfb link|year=1934|team=Wiley Wildcats|title=Wiley}}|Fair Park Stadium|[[Marshall, TX]]|W 33-0|2,000|<ref>{{cite news|title=Wiley Loses By Score of 33-0|newspaper=The Marshall News Messenger|date=December 9, 1934|page=8|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39629484/wiley_loses_by_score_of_330/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ky. State Thorobreds Trample Wiley, 33 to 0: Edwards Runs Wild As Ponies Beat Cats|newspaper=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=December 15, 1934|page=II-5|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39629781/ky_state_thorobreds_trample_wiley_33/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky State Thorobreds football navbox}}\n{{Black college football national champion navbox}}\n\n[[Category:1934 college football season|Kentucky State]]\n[[Category:Kentucky State Thorobreds football seasons]]\n[[Category:Black college football national champions]]\n[[Category:College football undefeated seasons]]\n[[Category:1934 in sports in Kentucky|Kentucky State Thorobreds football]]"
